  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How many types of metadata are there?",
  "response": "Metadata can be categorized into several types based on its function and content. The main types of metadata include:\n\n1. **Descriptive Metadata**: This type provides information about the content, such as the title, author, abstract, and keywords. It helps in discovering and identifying resources.\n\n2. **Structural Metadata**: It details the organization and hierarchy of the data, describing how different elements of a resource are connected. This is common in complex digital objects like datasets, video recordings, or digitized manuscripts.\n\n3. **Administrative Metadata**: This includes information to help manage resources, including rights management, preservation metadata, and technical specifications like file formats, creation dates, and access restrictions.\n\n4. **Reference Metadata**: This supports how data is collected, processed, and the quality it holds. It includes information about the methodology, data collection standards, and the statistical processes applied.\n\n5. **Statistical Metadata**: Mainly found in statistical contexts, this deals with the information about data points, variables, and datasets, describing their format and structure.\n\n6. **Legal Metadata**: Information about the legal status, intellectual property rights, and usage conditions.\n\nThese types can overlap and complement each other depending on the context and specific requirements of the dataset or resource being described. Additionally, communities of practice might have their own specific metadata schemas or standards based on their particular needs.",
